institution_blurb":"Yale University class of 1953 (B.A.)."}],"narrative_blocks":[{"header":"He won Olympic gold in sailing at Helsinki","body":"John Adams Morgan competed at the 1952 Summer Olympics in Helsinki in the 6 Metre class, winning gold with the boat Llanoria as part of a six-person crew. He was 21 years old. He graduated from Yale the following year, in 1953.","number":1},{"header":"He started Morgan Joseph because 'the pace is","body":"After careers at Dominick & Dominick and Smith Barney (VP and vice chairman of M&A), Morgan told the New York Times in 1986: 'The physical and mental pressures of investment banking are tremendous. Here the atmosphere is more pleasant and the pace is survivable.' The Times noted that in banking 'pedigree opens doors' — his Morgan name built 'the network of relationships, alliances and directorships that has made his small house among the most profitable of the new investment boutiques.' He co-founded Morgan Joseph in 2002 and chaired it until 2016.","number":2},{"header":"He owned a 3.5-acre private island off Stamford","body":"John Adams Morgan owned Caritas Island, a 3.5-acre private island compound off the coast of Stamford, Connecticut, with a 26-room, 14,000-square-foot home originally built in 1906. He listed it for sale in 2011 for $18.9 million.","number":3},{"header":"He served on the Morgan Library board","body":"John Adams Morgan served on the board of directors of the Morgan Library & Museum (LMK040) for 35 years, until his death in January 2025. He was the great-grandson of J.P. Morgan, the Library's founder, and the son of Henry Sturgis Morgan, its longtime president and chairman.","number":4}],"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"John Adams Morgan","first_name":"John","last_name":"Morgan","married_names":[],"middle_name":"Adams"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"s